NOTES\
- When the code is under the code ownership and responsibility of the author, it colours their expectation on the code quality - they expect it is probably correct and the code quality is better, they don\'92t need to check the formatting and code style. They also have less tendency to reach to other people less. If someone else would author the code, they would expect the project lead to do the review themselves.\
- Issues that do not relate to the change and are not doing anything at this point are something that should be fixed.\
- It does not scare them that there was a variable unrelated to the purpose of the change. Their concern is that the author introduced a variable but it was never used. Maybe the author forgot to do something but they do not think so because the purpose of the change is something else. The author probably introduced it during his work and then they changed their mind. Maybe the author wanted to do something broader and thought they would use this thing and then realised it is outside of the scope. That seems like the most likely scenario. Having that thing would make sense in the broader context,  but it\'92s not part of the problem they were trying to solve.\
- Another context, but they do not think it applies here - if the variable would be introduced as part of the broader context would be part of the customer facing maintenance branch so they are far more concerned about it and then they would suggest to separate the contribution to a different piece of work. The author should focus on fixing the bug that they are addressing and then do the other work separately. That would be just if it is someone internal, otherwise if there is a contribution from the community they would not care about their maintenance branch. But that does not come up very often.\
- The way of putting comments when they know something is wrong but write only an understanding question is dependent a lot on the receiver of the comment. They work with the author for a long time. They know it\'92s wrong, they don\'92t want to spend the time and go check and they have confidence from past experience that the author will fix it just by asking that question.\
- They definitely often ask for changes but subtly. They are a group of people working together for a very long time and there is no urgency in this situation so there is no pressure to move.\
- They do this a lot, but also when they are in a hurry or not in the mood they do it less.\
- Even if the colleagues would be fine with them being more brusk, it would wear over time. SO whenever they can be polite they try to do that. It looks better.\
- Also, they are a leader in this whole organisation so they are modelling the behaviour. SO they want to showcase the polite way to interact. Maybe no-one else will see this PR and the author is a long standing member part of their culture, so they do not need this modelling behaviour. But it would be if someone else would see it.\
- Sometimes they pull the PR first to the IDE and start the review that way. Typically, they don\'92t do that because it takes more effort. You have to switch much more between the GitHub and the IDE and it disrupts the whole working environment.\
- Typically starts to first use the GitHub itself and then jump away from that at some point.\
- Typically does not try to run the code, there is testing for that. But they did not focus on testing in this one that much other than the fact that the author was doing something.\
-   The IDE is much more efficient for going through the code than scrolling up and down. You can search for relationships and all that kind of stuff. Once they realise that is what they are going to be doing, that\'92s when they get the IDE.\
- The IDE said in this one that the variable is not used just by looking at the variable. They might never thought that otherwise. You can do searches and see which things are being used\'85 Once it starts to be that kind of stuff than they tend to go to the IDE.\
- They also use it when they want to see closer the related code, other classes and what they are doing, make sure they are right about how things work.\
- The limit to the depth of the review is dependent a lot on the people. This author works on this project for a long time, but they are things to look out for. The last issue they were checking is a very significant thing architecturally. It was probably fine, but it was potential future bug. They made sure they knew what was the data and where was it coming from, but in general they do not need to worry with this author whether they made simple trivial code mistakes. With someone junior they would be more careful.\
- Their culture in testing is not the best. They just checked the tests. If they would come back to this review they would probably check the tests more, make sure it is being tested.\
- When they look at tests it is more like - are there tests, do they seem to be covering the cases? There are certain things they keep an eye on in test cases like making sure they work fine and don\'92t use things incorrectly. They are things over time that do cause problems or don\'92t.\
- It is an important part of the review that they have the experience knowledge ready to pick the issues when they see them. They do a lot of code review and have done them for a long time and most people they work with have been doing this for a long time too so when there is the knowledge, it gets far more efficient.\
- When there are contributions from more junior people or that are not done by the in-house colleagues they have to be much more careful, consider more how to express things not to make people sad and not allow stuff you don\'92t want just to be nice. It\'92s harder. You want to encourage people to contribute to OSS. You also don\'92t have the lasting relationship with them. SO you need to be encouraging. They don\'92t need to be encouraging to the author of this PR.\
- Obviously if you are encouraging, keep a good relationship and behave nicely to people it works for everyone, but if you encourage the volunteers they contribute to the project.\
- Even people that are in-house or don\'92t work for the company can contribute outside of their scope and you want to be encouraging people to do so. So you want to have that in mind when you approach the review. You don\'92t want people to feel embarrassed or bad about their work. There is much more thanks.\
- For example when they submitted this review, they did not even comment, just sent the request changes.\
- The encouraging content is normally in the overall review comment. Sometimes they also comment that something is a good idea or that they like it.\
- Another thing they do with anybody which we could see in the first review - if there is an opportunity to be educative, they try to be educative. If something useful can be achieved with a low amount of effort\'85 That\'92s probably wy someone recommended them as doing good code reviews.\
- In some other review they showed the author a technique for writing tests that will be generally useful for years. It was a bit off topic, but educational. So they try to do that. It helps people to understand the overall culture of the project and it is a huge project so there is a lot of pieces of knowledge that can be disseminated. So if you do that it is encouraging to people because they feel they are progressing. You are not just fixing things, they are actually getting a benefit out of that process and they are learning. }